Great — here’s the full (latest) syllabus for PCAP‑31‑03 (Python Institute) — a “checklist-style” breakdown you can use to prepare.

======================================================
PCAP-31-03 — Full Syllabus Overview

Exam structure: 40 items, ~ 65 minutes, passing mark 70%. 
pythoninstitute.org
+1

Exam covers 5 major sections
===========================================
| Section                                                                                                                  | % of Exam / No. Items                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                          | Topics & Sub-topics (what you need to know) |
| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ | ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------- |
| **1. Modules & Packages** (12%) — 6 items ([pythoninstitute.org][1])                                                     | - Import and using modules/packages: all import variants (`import`, `from … import`, `as`, `from … import *`), nested modules, `dir()` function, `sys.path` variable. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Use standard library modules: <ul><li>**math** — functions like `ceil()`, `floor()`, `trunc()`, `factorial()`, `hypot()`, `sqrt()` </li><li>**random** — `random()`, `seed()`, `choice()`, `sample()` ([Mindasys |][3])</li><li>**platform** — functions like `platform()`, `machine()`, `processor()`, `system()`, `version()`, `python_implementation()`, `python_version_tuple()` ([Mindasys |][3])</li></ul> <br>- Create and use user-defined modules/packages: understanding `__init__.py`, `__pycache__`, `__name__`, public/private variables, package directory structures, nested packages. ([pythoninstitute.org][2])                                                                                                                                                        |                                             |
| **2. Exceptions** (14%) — 5 items ([pythoninstitute.org][1])                                                             | - Basic error handling using Python built-in exceptions: `try`, `except`, `else`, exception hierarchies, `raise`, `assert` statements, catching multiple exceptions (e.g. `except (E1, E2)`), retrieving exception arguments (`.args`), using `except E as e`. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Defining and using custom (user-defined) exceptions: extending exception hierarchy, integrating custom exceptions appropriately. ([pythoninstitute.org][2])                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    |                                             |
| **3. Strings** (18%) — 8 items ([pythoninstitute.org][1])                                                                | - Character representation & encoding: ASCII, Unicode, UTF-8, code points, escape sequences. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Basic string operations: using `ord()` and `chr()`, indexing, slicing, immutability, iterating, concatenation, repetition, comparisons, membership operators (`in`, `not in`). ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Built-in string methods and operations: methods like `.isxxx()`, `.join()`, `.split()`, plus using functions such as `sorted()`; search methods `.index()`, `.find()`, `.rfind()` for locating substrings. ([cramkey.com][4])                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    |                                             |
| **4. Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** (34%) — 12 items ([pythoninstitute.org][1])                                     | - Basic OOP concepts: class, object, property, method, encapsulation, inheritance (superclass/subclass), identifying class components. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Class vs instance variables; understanding `__dict__` property (objects vs classes); public/private attributes; name-mangling for “private” attributes. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Defining and using methods; understanding use of `self`. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Introspection/reflection: using `hasattr()`, `__name__`, `__module__`, `__bases__` to inspect classes/objects. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Inheritance & class hierarchy: single and multiple inheritance, overriding, using `isinstance()`, polymorphism, overriding methods (e.g. `__str__`), handling “diamond inheritance” problems. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Object creation and initialization: defining constructors (i.e. `__init__`) and properly initializing instance variables. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) |                                             |
| **5. Miscellaneous** (22%) — 9 items. Covers list comprehensions, lambdas, closures, and I/O. ([pythoninstitute.org][1]) | - List comprehensions (simple and nested), using conditional filtering (`if`) inside comprehensions. ([cramkey.com][4]) <br>- Lambda (anonymous) functions: defining and using lambdas, passing lambdas to functions, using built-ins like `map()` and `filter()` with lambdas. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- Closures: understanding what closures are, how to define and use them. ([cramkey.com][4]) <br>- Input/Output (I/O): understanding I/O modes (text vs binary), predefined streams vs custom streams, concept of handles/streams. ([pythoninstitute.org][2]) <br>- File operations: using `open()`, reading/writing files with `.read()`, `.write()`, `.readline()`, `.readlines()`, closing files; also using `bytearray` as an I/O buffer; handling `errno`.                                                                                                                                                                                                                  |                                             |

